<p>Please note that this is a basic script and might need to be adjusted ba=

<p>Remember to enable binary logging in your MySQL server if it=E2=80=99s n=

ou will have to restore all databases to the same situation before starting=
 applying the binary logs</a><a href=3D"https://stackoverflow.com/questions=

ps, which logs all transactions made</a><a href=3D"https://stackoverflow.co=
m/questions/409046/what-is-the-best-way-to-do-incremental-backups-in-mysql"=
 class=3D"ac-anchor sup-target" target=3D"_blank" data-citationid=3D"be3b22=

<p>Please replace <code>DB_USER</code>, <code>DB_PASSWORD</code>, and <code=

<cib-code-block code-lang=3D"bash" clipboard-data=3D"#!/bin/bash

# MySQL user credentials
USER=3D'DB_USER'
PASSWORD=3D'DB_PASSWORD'
DATABASE=3D'DB_NAME'

# Directories for backup and binary logs
BACKUP_DIR=3D&quot;/path/to/your/backup/directory&quot;
BINLOG_DIR=3D&quot;/var/log/mysql&quot;  # default directory for binary log=
s

# Timestamp
TIMESTAMP=3D$(date +&quot;%F&quot;)

# Create a full backup with mysqldump
mysqldump --user=3D${USER} --password=3D${PASSWORD} ${DATABASE} > &quot;${B=
ACKUP_DIR}/${DATABASE}_${TIMESTAMP}.sql&quot;

# Copy binary log for incremental backup
cp &quot;${BINLOG_DIR}/mysql-bin.000001&quot; &quot;${BACKUP_DIR}/${DATABAS=
E}_binlog_${TIMESTAMP}.log&quot;  # replace with your actual binary log fil=

></div></button></div><div class=3D"ac-horizontal-separator" aria-hidden=3D=
"true" style=3D""></div><div class=3D"ac-textBlock" style=3D""><p>High Avai=
lability (HA) is a critical aspect of any database system, including MySQL.=
 <a href=3D"https://www.mysql.com/products/enterprise/high_availability.htm=
l" class=3D"tooltip-target" data-citationid=3D"6140c74b-24a6-35a5-1ba0-520d=
8a841a82-7-group" h=3D"ID=3DSERP,5015.1">It ensures that your database is c=
ontinuously operational, even in the event of a failure</a><a href=3D"https=
://www.mysql.com/products/enterprise/high_availability.html" class=3D"ac-an=
chor sup-target" target=3D"_blank" data-citationid=3D"6140c74b-24a6-35a5-1b=
a0-520d8a841a82-5" aria-label=3D"1: " h=3D"ID=3DSERP,5015.1"><sup class=3D"=
citation-sup">1</sup></a><a href=3D"https://hevodata.com/learn/mysql-high-a=
vailability/" class=3D"ac-anchor sup-target" target=3D"_blank" data-citatio=
nid=3D"6140c74b-24a6-35a5-1ba0-520d8a841a82-7" aria-label=3D"2: " h=3D"ID=
=3DSERP,5015.1"><sup class=3D"citation-sup">2</sup></a>.</p>
<p>MySQL provides several solutions for high availability:</p>
<ol>
<li>
<p><strong>MySQL InnoDB Cluster</strong>: This is a built-in solution provi=
ded by MySQL that delivers a complete high availability solution. <a href=
=3D"https://www.mysql.com/products/enterprise/high_availability.html" class=
=3D"tooltip-target" data-citationid=3D"6140c74b-24a6-35a5-1ba0-520d8a841a82=
-14-group" h=3D"ID=3DSERP,5015.1">Each server in an InnoDB Cluster replicat=
es data to all members of the cluster while providing fault tolerance, auto=
mated failover, and elasticity</a><a href=3D"https://www.mysql.com/products=
/enterprise/high_availability.html" class=3D"ac-anchor sup-target" target=
=3D"_blank" data-citationid=3D"6140c74b-24a6-35a5-1ba0-520d8a841a82-14" ari=
a-label=3D"1: MySQL InnoDB Cluster" h=3D"ID=3DSERP,5015.1"><sup class=3D"ci=
tation-sup">1</sup></a>. <a href=3D"https://www.mysql.com/products/enterpri=
se/high_availability.html" class=3D"tooltip-target" data-citationid=3D"6140=
c74b-24a6-35a5-1ba0-520d8a841a82-16-group" h=3D"ID=3DSERP,5015.1">It also p=
rovides built-in group membership management, data consistency guarantees, =
node failure detection, and database failover, without the need for manual =
intervention</a><a href=3D"https://www.mysql.com/products/enterprise/high_a=
vailability.html" class=3D"ac-anchor sup-target" target=3D"_blank" data-cit=
ationid=3D"6140c74b-24a6-35a5-1ba0-520d8a841a82-16" aria-label=3D"1: Each s=
erver in an InnoDB Cluster replicates data to all members of the cluster wh=
ile providing fault tolerance, automated failover, and elasticity1" h=3D"ID=
=3DSERP,5015.1"><sup class=3D"citation-sup">1</sup></a>.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p><a href=3D"https://www.mysql.com/products/enterprise/high_availability.h=
tml" class=3D"tooltip-target" data-citationid=3D"6140c74b-24a6-35a5-1ba0-52=
0d8a841a82-21-group" h=3D"ID=3DSERP,5015.1"><strong>MySQL InnoDB ClusterSet=
</strong>: This provides disaster tolerance for InnoDB Cluster deployments =
by linking a primary InnoDB Cluster with one or more replicas of itself in =
different datacenters</a><a href=3D"https://www.mysql.com/products/enterpri=
se/high_availability.html" class=3D"ac-anchor sup-target" target=3D"_blank"=
 data-citationid=3D"6140c74b-24a6-35a5-1ba0-520d8a841a82-21" aria-label=3D"=
1: MySQL InnoDB ClusterSet" h=3D"ID=3DSERP,5015.1"><sup class=3D"citation-s=
up">1</sup></a>. <a href=3D"https://www.mysql.com/products/enterprise/high_=
availability.html" class=3D"tooltip-target" data-citationid=3D"6140c74b-24a=
6-35a5-1ba0-520d8a841a82-23-group" h=3D"ID=3DSERP,5015.1" target=3D"_blank"=
>If the primary cluster becomes unavailable due to the loss of the data cen=
ter or the loss of network connectivity, you can make a replica cluster act=
ive instead to restore the availability of the service</a><a href=3D"https:=
//www.mysql.com/products/enterprise/high_availability.html" class=3D"ac-anc=
hor sup-target" target=3D"_blank" data-citationid=3D"6140c74b-24a6-35a5-1ba=
0-520d8a841a82-23" aria-label=3D"1: MySQL InnoDB ClusterSet: This provides =
disaster tolerance for InnoDB Cluster deployments by linking a primary Inno=
DB Cluster with one or more replicas of itself in different datacenters1" h=
=3D"ID=3DSERP,5015.1"><sup class=3D"citation-sup">1</sup></a>.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p><a href=3D"https://hevodata.com/learn/mysql-high-availability/" class=3D=
"tooltip-target hover" data-citationid=3D"6140c74b-24a6-35a5-1ba0-520d8a841=
a82-28-group" h=3D"ID=3DSERP,5015.1" target=3D"_blank"><strong>Corosync, Pa=
cemaker, and Resource Agent</strong>: These are components of another high =
availability framework for MySQL</a><a href=3D"https://hevodata.com/learn/m=
ysql-high-availability/" class=3D"ac-anchor sup-target" target=3D"_blank" d=
ata-citationid=3D"6140c74b-24a6-35a5-1ba0-520d8a841a82-28" aria-label=3D"2:=
 Corosync, Pacemaker, and Resource Agent" h=3D"ID=3DSERP,5015.1"><sup class=
=3D"citation-sup">2</sup></a>. <a href=3D"https://www.mysql.com/products/en=
terprise/high_availability.html" class=3D"tooltip-target" data-citationid=
=3D"6140c74b-24a6-35a5-1ba0-520d8a841a82-30-group" h=3D"ID=3DSERP,5015.1">C=
orosync is a group communication system, Pacemaker is a high-availability r=
esource manager, and Resource Agent is a script that abstracts the service =
that is managed</a><a href=3D"https://hevodata.com/learn/mysql-high-availab=
ility/" class=3D"ac-anchor sup-target" target=3D"_blank" data-citationid=3D=
"6140c74b-24a6-35a5-1ba0-520d8a841a82-30" aria-label=3D"2: Corosync, Pacema=
ker, and Resource Agent: These are components of another high availability =
framework for MySQL2" h=3D"ID=3DSERP,5015.1"><sup class=3D"citation-sup">2<=
/sup></a>.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p><a href=3D"https://www.mysql.com/products/enterprise/high_availability.h=
tml" class=3D"tooltip-target" data-citationid=3D"6140c74b-24a6-35a5-1ba0-52=
0d8a841a82-35-group" h=3D"ID=3DSERP,5015.1"><strong>MySQL Group Replication=
</strong>: This is a MySQL Server plugin that provides distributed state ma=
chine replication with strong coordination between servers</a><a href=3D"ht=
tps://hevodata.com/learn/mysql-high-availability/" class=3D"ac-anchor sup-t=
arget" target=3D"_blank" data-citationid=3D"6140c74b-24a6-35a5-1ba0-520d8a8=
41a82-35" aria-label=3D"2: MySQL Group Replication" h=3D"ID=3DSERP,5015.1">=
<sup class=3D"citation-sup">2</sup></a>. <a href=3D"https://hevodata.com/le=
arn/mysql-high-availability/" class=3D"tooltip-target hover" data-citationi=
d=3D"6140c74b-24a6-35a5-1ba0-520d8a841a82-37-group" h=3D"ID=3DSERP,5015.1" =
target=3D"_blank">It guarantees that data is consistent across servers in a=
 group, and servers can leave and join the group and the group reconfigures=
 itself accordingly</a><a href=3D"https://hevodata.com/learn/mysql-high-ava=
ilability/" class=3D"ac-anchor sup-target" target=3D"_blank" data-citationi=
d=3D"6140c74b-24a6-35a5-1ba0-520d8a841a82-37" aria-label=3D"2: MySQL Group =
Replication: This is a MySQL Server plugin that provides distributed state =
machine replication with strong coordination between servers2" h=3D"ID=3DSE=
RP,5015.1"><sup class=3D"citation-sup">2</sup></a>.</p>
</li>
</ol>
<p>Remember, the choice of a high availability solution depends on your spe=
cific use case and requirements. <a href=3D"https://www.percona.com/blog/ch=
oosing-mysql-high-availability-solutions/" class=3D"tooltip-target" data-ci=
tationid=3D"6140c74b-24a6-35a5-1ba0-520d8a841a82-40-group" h=3D"ID=3DSERP,5=
015.1" target=3D"_blank">You might want to consider factors such as the siz=
e of your database, the acceptable downtime, the nature of your workload, a=
nd the resources at your disposal</a><a href=3D"https://www.percona.com/blo=
g/choosing-mysql-high-availability-solutions/" class=3D"ac-anchor sup-targe=
t" target=3D"_blank" data-citationid=3D"6140c74b-24a6-35a5-1ba0-520d8a841a8=
2-40" aria-label=3D"3: " h=3D"ID=3DSERP,5015.1"><sup class=3D"citation-sup"=
>3</sup></a>.</p>
</div> <div class=3D"ac-horizontal-separator" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D=
""></div></div>

DATABASE=3D'DB_NAME'

# Directories for backup and binary logs
BACKUP_DIR=3D"/path/to/your/backup/directory"
BINLOG_DIR=3D"/var/log/mysql"  # default directory for binary logs

# Timestamp
TIMESTAMP=3D$(date +"%F")

# Create a full backup with mysqldump
mysqldump --user=3D${USER} --password=3D${PASSWORD} ${DATABASE} &gt; "${BAC=
KUP_DIR}/${DATABASE}_${TIMESTAMP}.sql"

# Copy binary log for incremental backup
cp "${BINLOG_DIR}/mysql-bin.000001" "${BACKUP_DIR}/${DATABASE}_binlog_${TIM=
ESTAMP}.log"  # replace with your actual binary log file

HOW this creat incremental bakup?</div>

      <!----><div class=3D"ac-container ac-adaptiveCard" style=3D""><div cl=
ass=3D"ac-textBlock" style=3D""><p>The script you posted creates a full bac=
kup of your MySQL database and then copies the binary log for incremental b=
ackups. Here=E2=80=99s how it works:</p>
<ol>
<li>
<p><strong>Full Backup</strong>: The <code>mysqldump</code> command is used=
 to create a full backup of your database. This command connects to the MyS=
QL server and writes a SQL script that can be used to recreate the database=
. The output of this command is redirected to a <code>.sql</code> file in y=
our backup directory.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p><strong>Incremental Backup</strong>: The <code>cp</code> command is used=
 to copy the binary log file to your backup directory. The binary log conta=
ins a record of all changes to the database. It=E2=80=99s used for incremen=
tal backups because it allows you to apply changes that were made after the=
 full backup.</p>
</li>
</ol>
<p>To restore your database from these backups, you would first restore the=
 full backup using the <code>mysql</code> command to execute the <code>.sql=
</code> file. Then, you would use the <code>mysqlbinlog</code> command to a=
pply the changes from the binary log.</p>
<p>Please note that this script assumes that binary logging is enabled on y=
our MySQL server. If it=E2=80=99s not, you=E2=80=99ll need to enable it bef=
ore you can use this script for incremental backups.</p>
<p>Also, keep in mind that this is a basic script and might need to be adju=
sted based on your specific requirements and environment. Always test your =
backup strategy to ensure it works as expected before relying on it.</p>
<p>For more advanced backup strategies, you might want to look into tools l=
ike Percona XtraBackup. It=E2=80=99s an open-source hot backup utility for =
MySQL-based servers that doesn=E2=80=99t lock your database during the back=
up.</p>
</div></div>

      <!----><div class=3D"ac-container ac-adaptiveCard" style=3D""><div cl=
ass=3D"ac-textBlock" style=3D""><p>Sure, there are several server-side tool=
s that you can use to create MySQL dumps and manage file backups. Here are =
a few:</p>
<ol>
<li>
<p><strong>mysqldump</strong>: This is a command-line utility that comes wi=
th MySQL. <a href=3D"https://linuxize.com/post/how-to-back-up-and-restore-m=
ysql-databases-with-mysqldump/" class=3D"tooltip-target" data-citationid=3D=
"71fe70b1-231c-4234-4113-31d4e4e2d8e8-8-group" h=3D"ID=3DSERP,5015.1">It al=
lows you to create a SQL =E2=80=9Cdump=E2=80=9D of a database or a collecti=
on of databases for backup or transfer to another SQL server</a><a href=3D"=
https://linuxize.com/post/how-to-back-up-and-restore-mysql-databases-with-m=
ysqldump/" class=3D"ac-anchor sup-target" target=3D"_blank" data-citationid=
=3D"71fe70b1-231c-4234-4113-31d4e4e2d8e8-6" aria-label=3D"1: mysqldump" h=
=3D"ID=3DSERP,5015.1"><sup class=3D"citation-sup">1</sup></a><a href=3D"htt=
ps://serverguy.com/servers/how-to-backup-mysql-database/" class=3D"ac-ancho=
r sup-target" target=3D"_blank" data-citationid=3D"71fe70b1-231c-4234-4113-=
31d4e4e2d8e8-8" aria-label=3D"2: mysqldump" h=3D"ID=3DSERP,5015.1"><sup cla=
ss=3D"citation-sup">2</sup></a>. <a href=3D"https://linuxize.com/post/how-t=
o-back-up-and-restore-mysql-databases-with-mysqldump/" class=3D"tooltip-tar=
get" data-citationid=3D"71fe70b1-231c-4234-4113-31d4e4e2d8e8-13-group" h=3D=
"ID=3DSERP,5015.1">The <code>mysqldump</code> command can be used to backup=
 your database to a SQL file, which can then be backed up along with your o=
ther files</a><a href=3D"https://linuxize.com/post/how-to-back-up-and-resto=
re-mysql-databases-with-mysqldump/" class=3D"ac-anchor sup-target" target=
=3D"_blank" data-citationid=3D"71fe70b1-231c-4234-4113-31d4e4e2d8e8-11" ari=
a-label=3D"1: mysqldump" h=3D"ID=3DSERP,5015.1"><sup class=3D"citation-sup"=
>1</sup></a><a href=3D"https://serverguy.com/servers/how-to-backup-mysql-da=
tabase/" class=3D"ac-anchor sup-target" target=3D"_blank" data-citationid=
=3D"71fe70b1-231c-4234-4113-31d4e4e2d8e8-13" aria-label=3D"2: mysqldump" h=
=3D"ID=3DSERP,5015.1"><sup class=3D"citation-sup">2</sup></a>.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p><strong>mysqlhotcopy</strong>: This is a Perl script also included with =
MySQL that uses FLUSH TABLES, LOCK TABLES, and cp or scp to make a database=
 backup. <a href=3D"https://linuxize.com/post/how-to-back-up-and-restore-my=
sql-databases-with-mysqldump/" class=3D"tooltip-target" data-citationid=3D"=
71fe70b1-231c-4234-4113-31d4e4e2d8e8-18-group" h=3D"ID=3DSERP,5015.1">It is=
 a fast way to make a backup of the database or single tables, but it can b=
e run only on the same machine where the database directories are located</=
a><a href=3D"https://www.comparitech.com/net-admin/best-mysql-backup-tools/=
" class=3D"ac-anchor sup-target" target=3D"_blank" data-citationid=3D"71fe7=
0b1-231c-4234-4113-31d4e4e2d8e8-18" aria-label=3D"3: mysqlhotcopy" h=3D"ID=
=3DSERP,5015.1"><sup class=3D"citation-sup">3</sup></a>.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p><strong>Percona XtraBackup</strong>: This is an open-source hot backup s=
oftware for MySQL servers that offers backups without interrupting MySQL. <=
a href=3D"https://linuxize.com/post/how-to-back-up-and-restore-mysql-databa=
ses-with-mysqldump/" class=3D"tooltip-target" data-citationid=3D"71fe70b1-2=
31c-4234-4113-31d4e4e2d8e8-23-group" h=3D"ID=3DSERP,5015.1">It works with M=
ySQL, MariaDB, and Percona Server</a><a href=3D"https://www.comparitech.com=
/net-admin/best-mysql-backup-tools/" class=3D"ac-anchor sup-target" target=
=3D"_blank" data-citationid=3D"71fe70b1-231c-4234-4113-31d4e4e2d8e8-23" ari=
a-label=3D"3: Percona XtraBackup" h=3D"ID=3DSERP,5015.1"><sup class=3D"cita=
tion-sup">3</sup></a>.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p><a href=3D"https://linuxize.com/post/how-to-back-up-and-restore-mysql-da=
tabases-with-mysqldump/" class=3D"tooltip-target" data-citationid=3D"71fe70=
b1-231c-4234-4113-31d4e4e2d8e8-28-group" h=3D"ID=3DSERP,5015.1"><strong>Bac=
ula</strong>: Bacula is a set of Open Source, computer programs that permit=
 you (or the system administrator) to manage backup, recovery, and verifica=
tion of computer data across a network of computers of different kinds</a><=
a href=3D"https://www.comparitech.com/net-admin/best-mysql-backup-tools/" c=
lass=3D"ac-anchor sup-target" target=3D"_blank" data-citationid=3D"71fe70b1=
-231c-4234-4113-31d4e4e2d8e8-28" aria-label=3D"3: Bacula" h=3D"ID=3DSERP,50=
15.1"><sup class=3D"citation-sup">3</sup></a>.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p><a href=3D"https://linuxize.com/post/how-to-back-up-and-restore-mysql-da=
tabases-with-mysqldump/" class=3D"tooltip-target" data-citationid=3D"71fe70=
b1-231c-4234-4113-31d4e4e2d8e8-33-group" h=3D"ID=3DSERP,5015.1"><strong>Ipe=
rius Backup</strong>: This is a backup software that has several plans, and=
 the higher editions include specialized processes to backup MySQL database=
s</a><a href=3D"https://www.comparitech.com/net-admin/best-mysql-backup-too=
ls/" class=3D"ac-anchor sup-target" target=3D"_blank" data-citationid=3D"71=
fe70b1-231c-4234-4113-31d4e4e2d8e8-33" aria-label=3D"3: Iperius Backup" h=
=3D"ID=3DSERP,5015.1"><sup class=3D"citation-sup">3</sup></a>.</p>
</li>
</ol>
<p>Remember, the choice of a backup tool depends on your specific needs and=
 requirements. Always ensure to test your backup strategy to make sure it w=
orks as expected before relying on it.</p>
</div> <div class=3D"ac-horizontal-separator" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D=
""></div></div>

<p>Please replace <code>DB_USER</code>, <code>DB_PASSWORD</code>, <code>DB_=

# MySQL user credentials
USER=3D'DB_USER'

DATABASE=3D'DB_NAME'

# WordPress installation path
WP_PATH=3D'/path/to/your/wordpress/installation'

# Backup server address
BACKUP_SERVER=3D'user@backupserver:/path/to/backup/directory'

# Use rsync to transfer database backup and binary log to backup server
rsync -avz ${LOCAL_BACKUP_DIR}/${DATABASE}_${TIMESTAMP}.sql ${BACKUP_SERVER=

rsync -avz ${LOCAL_BACKUP_DIR}/${DATABASE}_binlog_${TIMESTAMP}.log ${BACKUP=

      <!----><div class=3D"ac-container ac-adaptiveCard" style=3D""><div cl=
ass=3D"ac-textBlock" style=3D""><p>Binary logging in MySQL is a feature tha=
t keeps a record of all changes to the database in the form of =E2=80=9Ceve=
nts=E2=80=9D. These events describe database changes such as table creation=
 operations or changes to table data. <a href=3D"https://sqlbak.com/blog/in=
cremental-mysql-server-backup-via-binary-log/" class=3D"tooltip-target" dat=
a-citationid=3D"4a017305-34d0-23ff-a0c3-430b81274eb7-2-group" h=3D"ID=3DSER=
P,5015.1">They also include information about how long each statement took =
that updated data</a><a href=3D"https://sqlbak.com/blog/incremental-mysql-s=
erver-backup-via-binary-log/" class=3D"ac-anchor sup-target" target=3D"_bla=
nk" data-citationid=3D"4a017305-34d0-23ff-a0c3-430b81274eb7-2" aria-label=
=3D"1: " h=3D"ID=3DSERP,5015.1"><sup class=3D"citation-sup">1</sup></a>.</p=
>
<p>In the context of incremental backups, binary logs are crucial. <a href=
=3D"https://sqlbak.com/blog/incremental-mysql-server-backup-via-binary-log/=
" class=3D"tooltip-target" data-citationid=3D"4a017305-34d0-23ff-a0c3-430b8=
1274eb7-5-group" h=3D"ID=3DSERP,5015.1">An incremental backup contains all =
the changes that have occurred to the database since the last backup</a><a =
href=3D"https://sqlbak.com/blog/incremental-mysql-server-backup-via-binary-=
log/" class=3D"ac-anchor sup-target" target=3D"_blank" data-citationid=3D"4=
a017305-34d0-23ff-a0c3-430b81274eb7-5" aria-label=3D"1: " h=3D"ID=3DSERP,50=
15.1"><sup class=3D"citation-sup">1</sup></a>. <a href=3D"https://sqlbak.co=
m/blog/incremental-mysql-server-backup-via-binary-log/" class=3D"tooltip-ta=
rget" data-citationid=3D"4a017305-34d0-23ff-a0c3-430b81274eb7-7-group" h=3D=
"ID=3DSERP,5015.1">These changes are recorded in the binary log, making it =
possible to take backups that contain only the changes (or =E2=80=9Cdeltas=
=E2=80=9D) since the last full or incremental backup</a><a href=3D"https://=
sqlbak.com/blog/incremental-mysql-server-backup-via-binary-log/" class=3D"a=
c-anchor sup-target" target=3D"_blank" data-citationid=3D"4a017305-34d0-23f=
f-a0c3-430b81274eb7-7" aria-label=3D"1: An incremental backup contains all =
the changes that have occurred to the database since the last backup1" h=3D=
"ID=3DSERP,5015.1"><sup class=3D"citation-sup">1</sup></a>. <a href=3D"http=
s://sqlbak.com/blog/incremental-mysql-server-backup-via-binary-log/" class=
=3D"tooltip-target" data-citationid=3D"4a017305-34d0-23ff-a0c3-430b81274eb7=
-9-group" h=3D"ID=3DSERP,5015.1">This substantially reduces the size of bac=
kups and allows you to make such backups very often</a><a href=3D"https://s=
qlbak.com/blog/incremental-mysql-server-backup-via-binary-log/" class=3D"ac=
-anchor sup-target" target=3D"_blank" data-citationid=3D"4a017305-34d0-23ff=
-a0c3-430b81274eb7-9" aria-label=3D"1: These changes are recorded in the bi=
nary log, making it possible to take backups that contain only the changes =
(or =E2=80=9Cdeltas=E2=80=9D) since the last full or incremental backup1" h=
=3D"ID=3DSERP,5015.1"><sup class=3D"citation-sup">1</sup></a>.</p>
<p><a href=3D"https://sqlbak.com/blog/incremental-mysql-server-backup-via-b=
inary-log/" class=3D"tooltip-target" data-citationid=3D"4a017305-34d0-23ff-=
a0c3-430b81274eb7-12-group" h=3D"ID=3DSERP,5015.1">Here=E2=80=99s a step-by=
-step process of how it works</a><a href=3D"https://sqlbak.com/blog/increme=
ntal-mysql-server-backup-via-binary-log/" class=3D"ac-anchor sup-target" ta=
rget=3D"_blank" data-citationid=3D"4a017305-34d0-23ff-a0c3-430b81274eb7-12"=
 aria-label=3D"1: " h=3D"ID=3DSERP,5015.1"><sup class=3D"citation-sup">1</s=
up></a>:</p>
<ol>
<li>The very first backup must be a full backup. You need to create a full =
backup via <code>mysqldump</code>.</li>
<li>Each incremental copy contains changes that have been created since the=
 last backup. These changes are recorded in the binary log.</li>
<li>To create an incremental backup, you would copy the binary log files si=
nce the last backup.</li>
<li>During a restore, you would first restore the full backup, and then app=
ly the incremental backups (i.e., the binary logs) in the order they were c=
reated.</li>
</ol>
<p>Remember, for binary logging to work, it must be enabled on your MySQL s=
erver. <a href=3D"https://sqlbak.com/blog/incremental-mysql-server-backup-v=
ia-binary-log/" class=3D"tooltip-target" data-citationid=3D"4a017305-34d0-2=
3ff-a0c3-430b81274eb7-22-group" h=3D"ID=3DSERP,5015.1">You can do this by a=
dding <code>log-bin=3Dmysql-bin</code> in your MySQL configuration file</a>=
<a href=3D"https://sqlbak.com/blog/incremental-mysql-server-backup-via-bina=
ry-log/" class=3D"ac-anchor sup-target" target=3D"_blank" data-citationid=
=3D"4a017305-34d0-23ff-a0c3-430b81274eb7-22" aria-label=3D"1: log-bin=3Dmys=
ql-bin" h=3D"ID=3DSERP,5015.1"><sup class=3D"citation-sup">1</sup></a>. Als=
o, be aware that the binary log includes changes for all databases. <a href=
=3D"https://sqlbak.com/blog/incremental-mysql-server-backup-via-binary-log/=
" class=3D"tooltip-target" data-citationid=3D"4a017305-34d0-23ff-a0c3-430b8=
1274eb7-24-group" h=3D"ID=3DSERP,5015.1" target=3D"_blank">You will have to=
 restore all databases to the same situation before starting applying the b=
inary logs</a><a href=3D"https://sqlbak.com/blog/incremental-mysql-server-b=
ackup-via-binary-log/" class=3D"ac-anchor sup-target" target=3D"_blank" dat=
a-citationid=3D"4a017305-34d0-23ff-a0c3-430b81274eb7-24" aria-label=3D"1: Y=
ou can do this by adding log-bin=3Dmysql-bin in your MySQL configuration fi=
le1" h=3D"ID=3DSERP,5015.1"><sup class=3D"citation-sup">1</sup></a>.</p>
<p>Binary logging has other benefits too. It is essential for replication, =
where the binary log on a master replication server provides a record of th=
e data changes to be sent to slave servers. <a href=3D"https://sqlbak.com/b=
log/incremental-mysql-server-backup-via-binary-log/" class=3D"tooltip-targe=
t" data-citationid=3D"4a017305-34d0-23ff-a0c3-430b81274eb7-27-group" h=3D"I=
D=3DSERP,5015.1" target=3D"_blank">Point-in-time recovery is also possible =
using the binary log</a><a href=3D"https://sqlbak.com/blog/incremental-mysq=
l-server-backup-via-binary-log/" class=3D"ac-anchor sup-target" target=3D"_=
blank" data-citationid=3D"4a017305-34d0-23ff-a0c3-430b81274eb7-27" aria-lab=
el=3D"1: " h=3D"ID=3DSERP,5015.1"><sup class=3D"citation-sup">1</sup></a>.<=
/p>
<p><a href=3D"https://sqlbak.com/blog/incremental-mysql-server-backup-via-b=
inary-log/" class=3D"tooltip-target" data-citationid=3D"4a017305-34d0-23ff-=
a0c3-430b81274eb7-30-group" h=3D"ID=3DSERP,5015.1" target=3D"_blank">Howeve=
r, please note that binary logging can have an impact on performance, but i=
s usually limited to high-load environments</a><a href=3D"https://sqlbak.co=
m/blog/incremental-mysql-server-backup-via-binary-log/" class=3D"ac-anchor =
sup-target" target=3D"_blank" data-citationid=3D"4a017305-34d0-23ff-a0c3-43=
0b81274eb7-30" aria-label=3D"1: " h=3D"ID=3DSERP,5015.1"><sup class=3D"cita=
tion-sup">1</sup></a>. <a href=3D"https://sqlbak.com/blog/incremental-mysql=
-server-backup-via-binary-log/" class=3D"tooltip-target" data-citationid=3D=
"4a017305-34d0-23ff-a0c3-430b81274eb7-32-group" h=3D"ID=3DSERP,5015.1" targ=
et=3D"_blank">It=E2=80=99s always recommended to test in your environment b=
efore deciding to enable binary logging</a><a href=3D"https://sqlbak.com/bl=
og/incremental-mysql-server-backup-via-binary-log/" class=3D"ac-anchor sup-=
target" target=3D"_blank" data-citationid=3D"4a017305-34d0-23ff-a0c3-430b81=
274eb7-32" aria-label=3D"1: However, please note that binary logging can ha=
ve an impact on performance, but is usually limited to high-load environmen=
ts1" h=3D"ID=3DSERP,5015.1"><sup class=3D"citation-sup">1</sup></a>.</p>
